South Africa Stocks Advance For a Third Day; Aveng, Kap, SacOil Are Active

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 
2011-03-01T16:03:26Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-01/stocks-in-south-africa-rise-for-third-day-coal-of-africa-kap-are-active.html
  South Africa ’s FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index snapped two days of gains, losing 221.36, or 0.7
percent, to 32,050.73 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.    Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ), the diversified mining company
that makes up 11 percent of South Africa’s benchmark stock
index, snapped three days of advances, slumping 3.97 rand, or
1.1 percent, to 373.03 rand. Copper fell as much as 1.1 percent
to $9,775 an ounce in  London .  BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ), the
world’s largest mining company, declined 2.99 rand, or 1.1
percent, to 274.01 rand.    Anglo Platinum Ltd . (AMS SJ), the world’s largest platinum
mining company, rose to the highest since Feb. 23, climbing 5
rand, or 0.7 percent, to 682 rand. Platinum advanced the most in
a week, adding as much as 1.4 percent to $1,832.75 an ounce.    Aveng Ltd . (AEG SJ), the country’s largest construction
company by market value, fell for the first day in three, losing
54 cents, or 1.5 percent, to 36.04 rand. The company has agreed
to pay 128.9 million rand ($18.5 million) to settle two
antitrust complaints. It also said earnings per share for the
six months to Dec. 31 are expected to fall by between 30 percent
and 35 percent from a year earlier.    Coal of Africa Ltd . (CZA SJ), a producer of the fuel in
South Africa, advanced the most since Jan. 6, jumping 38 cents,
or 3.8 percent, to 10.46 rand. The coal producer said its mining
right application for the Makhado Coking Coal Project has been
accepted by the country’s Department of Mineral Resources, which
it said now triggers the start “of a rigorous process required
for the final granting of a full mining right.”    Kap International Holdings Ltd . (KAP SJ), an investment
company, rose for the first time in four days, gaining 6 cents,
or 2.7 percent, to 2.31 rand. The company said earnings per
share excluding one-time items increased to 13.9 cents a shares
from 11 cents a year earlier in the first half through December.  SacOil Ltd. (SCL SJ), an oil and natural gas explorer, rose
to the highest level in nine months, adding 8 cents, or 4.1
percent, to 2.04 rand. The company said it has agreed to buy a
20 percent interest in the OPL 281 hydrocarbon field in Nigeria.  To contact the reporter on this story:
